article.description: Yolanda Griffith had 22 points and 12 rebounds in the Sacramento Monarchs' 69-64 victory over the Seattle Storm on Saturday night.
article.headline: Storm remain winless in Sacramento
article.linkText: Griffith, Monarchs continue mastery of Storm
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- It was Yolanda Griffith hurting the Seattle Storm on Saturday night, but DeMya Walker killed them.

	   Griffith had 22 points and 12 rebounds in the Sacramento Monarchs' 69-64 victory over the Storm, but Walker scored six of her nine points in a late 9-0 run as the Monarchs (5-7) erased a one-point deficit.

	   Walker tied it with a free throw, then scored on a driving layup to give Sacramento the lead for good at 58-56 with 2:53 remaining.

	   "I've got to be a spark, that's my role,'' said Walker. "I've got to play well or I'm not going to be out there.''

	   After Griffith scored inside, Walker grabbed a rebound, made a shot and put the Monarchs ahead 62-56 with 1:05 left.

	   Seattle coach Anne Donovan, who could be heard yelling at her team in the locker room after the game, was annoyed at the Storm's lack of rebounds. Sacramento had 14 offensive rebounds to Seattle's seven.

	   "All the hustle plays went to Sacramento,'' Donovan said. "Down the stretch they wanted the game more than we did.''

	   Lauren Jackson had 19 points and nine rebounds for Seattle (5-5), which had won five of six games, including a one-point victory earlier this week at first place Los Angeles.

	   Sue Bird had 14 points and six assists, and Sandy Brondello added 13 points for Seattle, which has lost nine of 11 overall to the Monarchs and never won in Sacramento.
